---
import SeriesHeroImage from '../../assets/skill-spotter-hero.png';
import Layout from '../../layouts/BlogPost.astro';

// Four skills that chain into one pipeline: spot the repeatable work, map the
// code read-only, plan it, hand it off. Presented in that order.
const skills = [
	{
		stage: 'Spot',
		href: '/blog/skill-spotter-claude-code-skill/',
		title: 'skill-spotter: notice repeatable work and offer to save it',
		blurb:
			'The one that starts it all. It watches for repetition and stated rules in a conversation, then offers to turn the pattern into a reusable skill, with a subagent review before anything gets saved.',
	},
	{
		stage: 'Understand',
		href: '/blog/code-review-recon-claude-code-skill/',
		title: 'code-review-recon: map a codebase before you touch it',
		blurb:
			'A deep, read-only sweep that maps the architecture and writes it down, touching nothing. The grounding every later step builds on, so the agent never edits code it does not understand.',
	},
	{
		stage: 'Plan',
		href: '/blog/dev-plan-claude-code-skill/',
		title: 'dev-plan: write plans a sub-agent can follow blindly',
		blurb:
			'Turn a vague request into a locked, phase-by-phase plan grounded in the files recon identified. It answers every question before anyone writes code, because headless workers cannot ask.',
	},
	{
		stage: 'Hand off',
		href: '/blog/dev-handoff-claude-code-skill/',
		title: 'dev-handoff: dispatch a dev plan to sub-agents',
		blurb:
			'Split the roles. A smart model plans and reviews; the actual typing goes to cheaper worker models running in parallel through OpenCode. The last step of the pipeline.',
	},
];
---

<Layout
	title="Claude Code skills I've built: a pipeline"
	description="Four Claude Code skills that chain into one workflow: spot the repeatable work, map the codebase read-only, turn it into a locked plan, and hand that plan to worker models. Each one is a standalone deep-dive on building custom Claude Code skills."
	kind="page"
	showDate={false}
	heroImage={SeriesHeroImage}
>
	<p class="whoami"><span class="prompt">~/$</span> ls ~/.claude/skills</p>

	<p>
		These are the <a href="https://claude.com/claude-code">Claude Code</a> skills I built for
		my own work, each written up as a standalone post. They are not really separate. They chain
		into one pipeline: notice the repeatable work, map the code without touching it, turn that
		into a plan a worker can follow blindly, and hand the plan off to run in parallel. Spot,
		understand, plan, hand off.
	</p>

	<p>
		The whole set exists because the first one, <code>skill-spotter</code>, kept nudging me to
		write each piece down instead of explaining it for the third time. Read them in pipeline
		order below, or jump straight to the stage you need.
	</p>

	<h2>The skills</h2>

	<ol class="parts">
		{
			skills.map((s) => (
				<li class="part done">
					<span class="badge live">{s.stage}</span>
					<a href={s.href}>{s.title}</a>
					<p>{s.blurb}</p>
				</li>
			))
		}
	</ol>

	<p class="closing">
		Spot, understand, plan, hand off, in that order, and each one earns its place by making the
		next possible. More skills join the shelf as I catch myself repeating the next thing.
	</p>
</Layout>

<style>
	.whoami {
		font-family: var(--font-mono);
		color: var(--sys-dim);
		margin-bottom: 1.5em;
	}
	.whoami .prompt {
		color: var(--sys-fg);
		font-weight: 700;
	}
	.parts {
		list-style: none;
		margin: 1.5em 0;
		padding: 0;
	}
	.part {
		border: 1px solid var(--sys-dim);
		border-left: 3px solid var(--sys-fg);
		padding: 1em 1.2em;
		margin: 0 0 1em;
	}
	.part .badge {
		display: inline-block;
		font-family: var(--font-mono);
		font-size: 0.75rem;
		text-transform: uppercase;
		letter-spacing: 0.06em;
		color: var(--sys-fg);
		margin-bottom: 0.4em;
	}
	.part a {
		display: block;
		font-family: var(--font-mono);
		font-weight: 700;
		font-size: 1.05rem;
		line-height: 1.3;
	}
	.part p {
		margin: 0.4em 0 0;
		font-size: 0.95rem;
		color: var(--sys-text);
	}
	.closing {
		margin-top: 1.5em;
	}
</style>
